    &lt;/span&gt;
While editing text files with &lt;strong&gt;vi/vim&lt;/strong&gt;, we often need the white space characters to be shown, like ‘\t’ (tabulation), ‘\n’ (end of line), and ’ ‘(space) to confirm the file syntax. How to show these characters in different ways? You may just use the following vim command,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;gatsby-highlight&quot; data-language=&quot;vim&quot;&gt;&lt;pre class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token keyword&quot;&gt;set&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;token keyword&quot;&gt;list&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By default, ‘\t’ is shown as ‘^I’, ‘\n’ is shown as ’$’, and ’ ’ is kept not changed. You may also want to customize the representations, this could be configured via the &lt;strong&gt;listchars/lcs&lt;/strong&gt; option, e.g,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;gatsby-highlight&quot; data-language=&quot;vim&quot;&gt;&lt;pre class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token keyword&quot;&gt;set&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;token builtin&quot;&gt;lcs&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token operator&quot;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token keyword&quot;&gt;tab&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token operator&quot;&gt;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token operator&quot;&gt;-&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;trail&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token operator&quot;&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token builtin&quot;&gt;eol&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;space&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;~&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You may refer to the vim help documents (section listchars) for more details.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;gatsby-highlight&quot; data-language=&quot;vim&quot;&gt;&lt;pre class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-vim&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token punctuation&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token keyword&quot;&gt;help&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;token builtin&quot;&gt;listchars&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Use Different Desktop Managers of Ubuntu]]></title><description><![CDATA[desktop managers are important to ubuntu GUI, it's useful to learn the method for changing them.]]></description><link>https://alexxyjiang.github.io/posts/use-different-desktop-managers-of-ubuntu</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://alexxyjiang.github.io/posts/use-different-desktop-managers-of-ubuntu</guid><pubDate>Sat, 21 Apr 2007 22:30:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span
      class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-wrapper&quot;
      style=&quot;position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; &quot;
    &gt;
      &lt;a
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-link&quot;
    href=&quot;/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg&quot;
    style=&quot;display: block&quot;
    target=&quot;_blank&quot;
    rel=&quot;noopener&quot;
  &gt;
    &lt;span
    class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-background-image&quot;
    style=&quot;padding-bottom: 56.25%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url(&apos;data:image/jpeg;base64,&apos;); background-size: cover; display: block;&quot;
  &gt;&lt;/span&gt;
  &lt;picture&gt;
          &lt;source
              srcset=&quot;/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/8ac56/ubuntu.webp 240w,
/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/d3be9/ubuntu.webp 480w,
/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/d00b9/ubuntu.webp 800w&quot;
              sizes=&quot;(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px&quot;
              type=&quot;image/webp&quot;
            /&gt;
          &lt;source
            srcset=&quot;/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/09b79/ubuntu.jpg 240w,
/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/7cc5e/ubuntu.jpg 480w,
/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg 800w&quot;
            sizes=&quot;(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px&quot;
            type=&quot;image/jpeg&quot;
          /&gt;
          &lt;img
            class=&quot;gatsby-resp-image-image&quot;
            src=&quot;/static/c85bd00ea2f07b2c39953bdd961cdbfb/4b190/ubuntu.jpg&quot;
            alt=&quot;ubuntu logo&quot;
            title=&quot;ubuntu logo&quot;
            loading=&quot;lazy&quot;
            style=&quot;width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;&quot;
          /&gt;
        &lt;/picture&gt;
  &lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First of all, X Window Core must be installed, or you won’t be able to use GUI. X Window Core is called “x-window-system-core”. To install any GUI, you should install this first.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In linux, one of the display managers (login managers) &lt;strong&gt;gdm/kdm/xdm&lt;/strong&gt; should be chosen. To get a different desktop manager for ubuntu, just add packages following:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;gnome&lt;/strong&gt;: ubuntu-desktop&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;kde&lt;/strong&gt;: kubuntu-desktop&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;xfce&lt;/strong&gt;: xubuntu-desktop&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;e.g.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;gatsby-highlight&quot; data-language=&quot;bash&quot;&gt;&lt;pre class=&quot;language-bash&quot;&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-bash&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;token comment&quot;&gt;# apt install ubuntu-desktop&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After the installation, of course, we should set default-display-manager on ubuntu. There are two ways to do so,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Edit file “/etc/X11/default-display-manager”, change display manager name in it and save, then reboot.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Run “dpkg-reconfigure gdm/kdm/xdm” to switch (gdm for gnome, kdm for kde, xdm for xfce), you will get a menu to choose. Of course you should do this as root, or “sudo”.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Refer to: &lt;a href=&quot;http://ubuntuforums.org/showthread.php?t=205002&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;HOWTO: correctly install/remove k/x/ed/ubuntu-desktop packages&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item></channel></rss>